posts.com:
Ok, weird personnal schyzo rambling by someone who doesn't exist.

I hate my body, I've spent countless nights crying on the floor, trying to rip this fleshy madness that is a male body. I only feel slightly confortable when presenting female and yet, I know I am not a "girl".
I dont know if this is coping from dooming for countless years in my male body. But feminity was a side I always wanted to express, since I was 5.
Puberty and how my body evolved during it made sure I couldn't be perceived and express myself to other how I wanted to be, so I transitionned, there was no option, beside killing myself once and for all.

I dont see myself as a "girl" as other perceive the gender. I understood that fairly late during my transition. The way societ, others, see a "girl", is simply not me.

>So what? I am DEFINETLY NOT a man, and not a girl, so what the fuck am I?

This transition for me was all about Identity, for 20 fucking years I never existed, and I have yet to exist. I have yet to express how I am.
And "girl" is just not it. I was always fine with androgeny, for whatever reasons. It just felt... right. I like to present myself as female, but I chose clothes on gender, rather what I felt was right. It just happened to be female presenting. I like being considered a female, but i'm more than just "that".
Transitioning made my relationship with gender very weird. And androgeny is right where I want to be. I dont want to be seen as either just a gender. I want to be seen as myself, and I've come to understand during transition that "myself" is not just "girl".

So am I even non-binary? I have no fucking clue.
In the end of the day, I still have to exist, my transition isn't finished, and my road to self discovery is FAR from over.

But androgeny will do just fine for now.
I just want to be myself, for one fucking second on this godforsaken place.

>Retinoic acid is a signaling molecule and causes changes at the DNA expression level. There's a retinoic acid receptor just like estrogen and testosterone and glucocorticoid receptors. You're supposed to stop using retin-A and accutane during pregnancy and breastfeeding for a reason: it will have systemic effects on a developing fetus and infant. Using a topical medication as an adult will not have the same effects as exposing a developing embryo or fetus to it.

Retinol is not as regulated. The justification for this is that first, retinol is a vitamin A derivative naturally found in an omnivorous diet. Secondly, retinol has to cross the skin barrier to the living cells underneath. Then retinol has to be converted to biologically active retinoids with an enzyme in the skin (human retinol dehydrogenase is the name of the enzyme if you want to look it up). This reaction is limited by both enzyme and substrate. Retinols will be destroyed over time by the presence of blue light/UV light. The best bet is to buy retinol from a large company that will be beholden to cGMP and quality assurance. I know that goes against a lot of the values here, but even an unregulated drug is still a drug and I wouldn't trust etsy to make my drugs.

Skincare blogging has become a cottage industry absolutely overcrowded with unqualified voices. Vitamin A derivatives are screened for cancer chemotherapeutic agents specifically because they are (1) potent and biologically active molecules and (2) (likely to be) safer than things like cisplatin because they are analogues of vitamin A instead of inorganic molecules that kill cells. Plant derivatives of vitamin A (carotenoids) like beta carotene and lycopene, are also screened for anti-cancer activity.

You know you're brainwormed, which is a good thing. Being in a good, mentally stable place before transitioning may be a sensible choice to make sure you don't immediately cave and detrans. These feelings of inadequacy will consume you if you let them, and weeding them out takes time and effort. Hard to overcome, but given some support and some personal progress you can overcome it. You can change your opinions of yourself. You can change plenty of your wants.
Tranners would however urge you to rather start sooner than later, because it improves your chances, and because there is a chance you will never feel ready. Never, ever set out to a loosely defined goal with ill defined preconditions like that. You will never feel ready then, and just append new arbitrary conditions when you will start for real. Set a clear, realistic, measurable goal. "When my BMI is 23 I will transition", for example. Stick to it, you will never feel adequate or prepared.

Do you feel disgusted by being a man? Would you pick to wake up as a cis woman tomorrow with no hesitation? If you were alone for life on a desert island and had male and female clothes and a lifetime supply of HRT sitting there, what would you do? Would you feel upset if a personality test guessed you're male? If there was a test to see for sure if you have gender dysphoria or not, what result would you hope for? Would you rather be the hottest hunk of a man to ever live or an average woman? Would you transition if everyone in society was totally fine with it? How about if you knew for sure you'd pass? Try sitting down and getting calm and kind of meditative and tell yourself repeatedly, "I am a man." How does that make you feel? How about the same thing with "I am a woman."? If you try it with, "I am going to stay a man for the rest of my life, I will never transition and I will die as a man," how does that feel? What about, "that's it, I'm done fighting feeling this way, I'm going to start transitioning as soon as possible," how does that make you feel?

Just a few exercises to kind of see. It's not definitive or anything but it might help.

There might be something going on if you've always felt like you've just been playing a character and you've always been detached and never present and like you're looking at someone else when you look in the mirror. Gender dysphoria causes this pervasive feeling of everything feeling wrong and off and like it's not quite real. Did you wish you were a girl as a kid? Ultimately it's up to you to decide if transition is worth it for you, and if the relief it would bring would be worth the risks and what you'd be losing. For me, it's definitely always been there and been a thorn in my side, but I finally stopped feeling denial a while back and admitted to myself that I'm trans, and ever since then I've felt some kind of relief not keeping it from myself and I've been taking better care of myself and caring more about my life and stuff, but at the same time I can't stop thinking about transitioning now and I want it more than anything. Alright trannies and others. I've been through enough of you that this needs to be said.
If you want a conversation to thrive to potentially make a friend, there generally needs to be a back and forth.
If I ask 3 or 4 things about you and you don't ask a single thing about me, you seem incredibly uninteresting and uninterested and you'll get ghosted 9/10 times because I don't have the time or the energy to walk you through basic human communication.
They ask something about you, you answer, if your answer is interesting, they'll follow up, if they can't, you ask a question about them.
Ask you
Ask them
Ask you
And don't do the 'wbu' thing if it can be helped.
Eventually hopefully you progress to the point it's comfortable to not be 1-1 with questions or info, but you need to make effort to start with, which is 90% of the problem for most of you.

Ohhh I see I see
Well, replacing sub with oral is a bit problematic, bcs you're going from higher avg/peak lvls w/sub to a lot lower with same mg sub to oral e2 dose.
to explain, oral takes awhile to buildup e2 lvls as your body is building up a reservoir of various sulfated/conjugated/weaker forms of estrogens that build up, which converts back to e2 making e2 lvls nice and steady plus higher e2 lvls on avg than single dose (takes a few weeks), and so if u rely on oral e2 without building up u can suddenly spike T lvls due to lacking antigonadatropin action of higher e2 like sub does.
so, it very well could of been a spike in T lvls, even just mid/high female T lvls, but that change from likely near zero T would be a bit of a shock to your system as likely sensitized ARs due to low T lvls for awhile+cypro being an AR antagonist

my advice in the future is to titrate your dose when changing it, so avoid that sudden shock like u experienced, and with oral e2 u wanna build up lvls first b4 relying on it

When I found myself blindsided in the ways I was, it took me years of truly horrific, life-ruining suffering to even begin to recover, let alone form any semblance of a healthy relationship, and even then, it's made establishing true closeness unimaginably rare and difficult.

To this day, surviving in a world like this is often incredibly lonely and difficult, and my one solace is seeing a level of truth that others have to go through immense hell to be aware of, and having the means to help others get through that hell and make sense of what happened to them has become incredibly important to me.

I'm so sorry your sense of personhood and trust in intimacy - or trust in others at all - was mortally scarred in the way it was, and I know how hard it must be to see reminders of your isolation and trauma every day in the supposedly good but callously violent intentions of others. I know what it does to you, and I wouldn't wish that nightmare on anyone.

You're not a monster. You've just seen more than most. I know how hard it can be to stomach it, but anchoring yourself and your reality with truth and complete, whole closeness in your relationships the best you can gives you strength in context and numbers. Know yourself, your story, your intentions, and how you communicate: each one is grounding, and together they make the senselessness of it all turn to an origin you can find your way through. Even when you don't want to make yourself vulnerable, bandage others in their own tightly-wound lacerations where and when you have the means, and you'll know you're not alone... and try your best not to judge either yourself or those you see hurting along the way. Everyone's got circumstances and does everything they do for a reason, and knowing that'll make things make a lot more sense than they have.

I know the perspective is painful and lonely, but it's unthinkably powerful, too. I know you're hurting, but you're more important than you ever have been.

Thumbs up Edition
previous: >>28926505

Goal of the thread: Work on one skill you wish to be better at. It can be as simple as reading a small paragraph of a text book on the subject.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

If any resource below is unhelpful, please let me know. I can't assert their quality on my own.

resources:

Exercise, diet, weight loss/gain: >>>/fit/17018018 (sticky)
NIMH brochures on mental health topics (Depression, BPD, ADHD, etc): https://www.nimh.nih.gov/health/publications
ED: https://www.eatingdisorderhope.com/treatment-for-eating-disorders

General advice from Anons: https://0x0.st/o5Og.txt

we currently lack (mental) health resources.
Suggestions and debate for which to include encouraged!

Additional resources:
Get started with weight loss (courtesy of /fit/fat/):
>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).
